1330":"1289–1330","1291–Male":"1291–Afdød","1242–Male":"1242–Afdød","1242":"1242","1330":"1330","1341":"1341","1285":"1285","Abt 1268":"omkring 1268","1291":"1291","Abt 1285":"omkring 1285","Abt 1284":"omkring 1284","1314":"1314","Abt 1289":"omkring 1289","1312":"1312","1268":"1268","1289":"1289","Abt 1287":"omkring 1287","1266":"1266","1287":"1287","Abt 1291":"omkring 1291","Of, Brampton, Lincolnshire, England":"Brampton, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Of, Enderby, Leicestershire, England":"Enderby, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Of, Holdenby, Northamptonshire, England":"Holdenby, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Of,, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1268–1312":"circa 1268–1312","1268–1312":"1268–1312","1266–1314":"1266–1314","1285–1341":"1285–1341","1287–Male":"1287–Overleden","1289–1330":"1289–1330","1291–Male":"1291–Overleden","1242–Male":"1242–Overleden","1242":"1242","1330":"1330","1341":"1341","1285":"1285","Abt 1268":"circa 1268","1291":"1291","Abt 1285":"circa 1285","Abt 1284":"circa 1284","1314":"1314","Abt 1289":"circa 1289","1312":"1312","1268":"1268","1289":"1289","Abt 1287":"circa 1287","1266":"1266","1287":"1287","Abt 1291":"circa 1291","Of, Brampton, Lincolnshire, England":"Brampton, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Of, Enderby, Leicestershire, England":"Enderby, Leicestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Of, Holdenby, Northamptonshire, England":"Holdenby, Northamptonshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Of,, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1268–1312":"about 1268–1312","1268–1312":"1268–1312","1266–1314":"1266–1314","1285–1341":"1285–1341","1287–Male":"1287–Deceased","1289–1330":"1289–1330","1291–Male":"1291–Deceased","1242–Male":"1242–Deceased","1242":"1242","1330":"1330","1341":"1341","1285":"1285","Abt 1268":"about 1268","1291":"1291","Abt 1285":"about 1285","Abt 1284":"about 1284","1314":"1314","Abt 1289":"about 1289","1312":"1312","1268":"1268","1289":"1289","Abt 1287":"about 1287","1266":"1266","1287":"1287","Abt 1291":"about 1291","Of, Brampton, Lincolnshire, England":"Brampton, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Of, Enderby, Leicestershire, England":"Enderby, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Of, Holdenby, Northamptonshire, England":"Holdenby, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Of,, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Scrope","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman: of uncertain origin. Tengvik suggests derivation from the Old Scandinavian personal name  <i>Skrópi</i> (of doubtful etymology, but compare Old Scandinavian  <i>skrópa-maðr</i> ‘hypocrite’, containing the genitive plural form of  <i>skrópar</i> ‘sham, hypocrisy’). It is possible, but not certain, that this personal name forms the first element of the Notts place-name Scrooby. Otherwise there is no evidence for its currency in England or, more relevantly, in Normandy. Richards Castle (in Herefs and Shrops) was apparently named after Richard Scrope, who held estates in Herefs and Worcs in 1066 and was a Norman favourite of Edward the Confessor. The Scrope family, whose name is traditionally pronounced /skru:p/, was politically important in medieval England, and acquired estates in Lincs (Barton on Humber), NR Yorks (Castle Bolton), and in ER Yorks (Flotmanby). Richard (le) Scrope of Bolton, in Wensleydale, was Lord Chancellor in the reign of Richard II. The use of  <i>le</i> and  <i>de</i> in the surname, suggesting either a nickname or a locative name, must be treated with caution because these were often added gratuitously to Anglo-Norman surnames as a sign of high social status."],"variants":[{"name":"Scroop","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Scrope  ."]},{"name":"Scroope","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Scrope  ."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud Scrope was born about 1268, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Henry Scrope. She married Sir Robert Neville about 1284, in Brampton, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died in 1312, at the age of 45."},"et":{"Abt 1268–1312":"umbes 1268–1312","1268–1312":"1268–1312","1266–1314":"1266–1314","1285–1341":"1285–1341","1287–Male":"1287–Surnud","1289–1330":"1289–1330","1291–Male":"1291–Surnud","1242–Male":"1242–Surnud","1242":"1242","1330":"1330","1341":"1341","1285":"1285","Abt 1268":"umbes 1268","1291":"1291","Abt 1285":"umbes 1285","Abt 1284":"umbes 1284","1314":"1314","Abt 1289":"umbes 1289","1312":"1312","1268":"1268","1289":"1289","Abt 1287":"umbes 1287","1266":"1266","1287":"1287","Abt 1291":"umbes 1291","Of, Brampton, Lincolnshire, England":"Brampton, Lincol